{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17592404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17592404"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:13:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:13:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15231"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15231","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15231"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.07,0,0.81,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7922"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65140"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7922"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15231"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50576"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"1449"},{"type":"tags","id":"2171"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5364"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19299"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19301"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21642"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65140"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She has no family history of colorectal cancer or other hereditary cancer syndromes. She is a non-smoker and consumes alcohol occasionally. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the primary prevention strategy for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Annual colonoscopy starting at age 50","Annual faecal occult blood test (FOBT) starting at age 25","Biennial colonoscopy starting at age 25","Biennial faecal occult blood test (FOBT) starting at age 45","Flexible sigmoidoscopy every five years starting at age 50"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is in the average risk Category 1 for colorectal cancer. The current recommendations are \u003Cstrong\u003Ebiennial faecal occult blood test (FOBT) starting at age 45\u003C/strong\u003E as the recommended primary prevention strategy for colorectal cancer in individuals with an average risk. This approach is effective in detecting early signs of colorectal cancer and has been shown to reduce mortality from the disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnnual colonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for average-risk individuals due to its invasive nature and the potential for complications. It is typically reserved for those at higher risk or with positive screening tests.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiennial colonoscopy starting at age 25\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for average-risk individuals. This approach is more suited for those with a significant family history or genetic predisposition to colorectal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexible sigmoidoscopy every five years\u003C/strong\u003E can be considered as an additional screening method for colorectal cancer in average-risk individuals, but it is not the primary strategy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnnual faecal occult blood test (FOBT) starting at age 25\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary for average-risk individuals. Screening typically begins at age 45 unless there are specific risk factors that warrant earlier intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese are the current guidelines:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 1 - similar risk as the general population\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with no family history of colorectal cancer OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne 1st-degree relative with CRC \u226560 years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: FOBT should be completed every 2 years from 45 years old as per usual screening protocol. Colonoscopy is generally not recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 2 - moderately increased risk\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with one 1st-degree relative CRC diagnosed \u0026lt;60 years OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age or one 1st-degree and two 2nd-degrees at any age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: Colonoscopy should be offered 5 yearly starting at \u003Cstrong\u003E10 years younger\u003C/strong\u003E than the earliest diagnosis of CRC in a 1st-degree relative, or age \u003Cstrong\u003E50 \u003C/strong\u003E(whichever is earliest).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 3 - high risk, excluding hereditary cancer syndromes\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic with two 1st-degree and one 2nd-degree relative with colorectal cancer, with at least one diagnosed before 50 years old OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives and two or more 2nd-degree relatives diagnosed with CRC at any age OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThree or more 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: refer to the familial cancer clinic for genetic assessment before a screening decision is made if Lynch syndrome has not been excluded. If Lynch syndrome is excluded, colonoscopy should be offered every 5 years starting at \u003Cstrong\u003E10 years younger\u003C/strong\u003E than the earliest age of diagnosis of colorectal cancer in a first-degree relative or age \u003Cstrong\u003E40 \u003C/strong\u003Eyears (whichever is earliest)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["For individuals at average risk of colorectal cancer, biennial faecal occult blood testing (FOBT) starting at age 50 is recommended as a primary prevention strategy.","Flexible sigmoidoscopy every five years can be considered as an additional screening method for colorectal cancer in average-risk individuals.","Colonoscopy is typically reserved for individuals at higher risk or those with positive screening tests."],"references":["Kumar R, Lewis CR. Colon Cancer Screening. [Updated 2024 Sep 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559064/","Lin JS, Perdue LA, Henrikson NB, Bean SI, Blasi PR. Screening for Colorectal Cancer: Updated Evidence Report and Systematic Review for the US Preventive Services Task Force. JAMA. 2021 May 18;325(19):1978-1998. doi: 10.1001/jama.2021.4417. Erratum in: JAMA. 2021 Jul 20;326(3):279. doi: 10.1001/jama.2021.10417. PMID: 34003220","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Shaukat A, Levin TR. Current and future colorectal cancer screening strategies. Nat Rev Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2022 Aug;19(8):521-531. doi: 10.1038/s41575-022-00612-y. Epub 2022 May 3. Erratum in: Nat Rev Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2022 Aug;19(8):551. doi: 10.1038/s41575-022-00661-3. PMID: 35505243; PMCID: PMC9063618"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50576"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15231"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50576"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T15:17:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T15:17:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7922"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65140"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"t